Part 1: Data

The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. Therefore, the data connot be used to establish causal relationships between variables of interest. Hence, the nature of this project serves as an observational study due to the random sampling. At first glance, by looking at the timespan of the collected data by summary(movies$thtr_relyear) can be generalized to the released movies between 1970 and 2014. potentially revealing biases to look out for are based the data comes from only two sources, rotten tomatoes and IMDB.

Part 2: Research question

Is there an association with a movies rating and its attributions (e.g.genre, runtime) in the given dataset. * * *

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

set up new dataframe for the variables we are interested in and omit al the NA values.

df <- movies %>%
  select(imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_rating, critics_score,
         audience_score, audience_rating, runtime, genre, 
         mpaa_rating, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win,
         title_type, best_pic_nom) %>%
        na.omit(df)

Part 4 : Modeling

Developing a model that best predicts an IMDB rating, A linear regression will be used through backward elimnation with an adjusted R-squared in order to create a parsimonious model and elimnating predictors that are not statistically significant with alpha = 0.05.

imdb_rating, imdb_num_votes, critics_rating, critics_score, audience_score, audience_rating, runtime, genre, mpaa_rating, best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, title_type

m1<-lm(imdb_rating ~ runtime + genre + mpaa_rating + best_actor_win + best_actress_win +  best_dir_win, data = df)

Final model

m3 <- lm(imdb_rating ~ runtime + genre + mpaa_rating + best_dir_win, data = df) summary(m3) m3-model gives us the best predictive model, with an adjusted R-squared of 0.3082. while managing as parsimonious as possible with 4 variables.

Interpretation

The adjusted R-squared is 0.2884 meaning that the model explains 28.84% of the variability in the IMDB rating of a movie. Therfore, the unexplained variability is the complement of (1-0.2884)= 71.16% in the dependent variable. meaning that the variables in the dataset do not have a strong capability to predict an IMDB-ratings.

Diagnostics

The following conditions must be met to satisfy the multiple regression model:

  1. The residuals of the model are nearly normal
  2. The variability of the residuals is nearly constant
  3. The residuals are independent

  4. Each variable is linearly related to the outcome

  5. Residuals nearly normal

hist(m3$residuals, breaks=20, ylim=range(0,100), xlab="Residuals", ylab="",
     main="Distribution of residuals", col="light blue")

    qqnorm(m3$residuals, xlim=range(-4, 4), main="Normal Q-Q plot of residuals", col="skyblue")
    qqline(m3$residuals)

2. variability is constant

plot(m3$residuals~m3$fitted, main="Residuals vs. fitted")

plot(abs(m3$residuals)~m3$fitted, main="Absolute value of residuals vs. fitted")

3. Residuals are indepdent

plot(m3$residuals, xlab="Data Collecting Order", ylab="Residuals", cex=.6, col="skyblue")
abline(0,0)

4. Each (numerical) variable is linearly related to the outcome

plot(m3$residuals ~ df$runtime, xlab="Runtime", ylab="Residuals", cex=.6, col="skyblue")
abline(0,0)

Part 5: Prediction

A prediction interval is an estimate of an interval in which future observations will fall, with a certain probability (commonly 95%), given what has already been observed. Therefore we will take a random movie from the IMDB database and attempt to predict its value according to made-up model. Film: Black Panther -IMDB-rating: 7.3 -runtime= 134 minutes -best_dir_win= no, -genre=Action & Adventure, -mpaa_rating=PG-13,

Blckpntr = data.frame(best_pic_nom="yes", best_pic_win="no", best_dir_win="no", genre="Action & Adventure",mpaa_rating="PG-13",runtime=c(134),top200_box="no")

predict(m3, Blckpntr, interval = "predict")
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 6.081494 4.262256 7.900732

The predicted rating of the movie is 6.08, with 95% prediction interval of [4.26, 7.9]. While actual rating of the movie is 7.3 which is within our prediction interval.

Part 6: Conclusion

Given the dataset and its given variables, the model explains 28.84% of the variation in the rating which is not very high, and for this reason the interval predicted will be wide. The dependent variable is the rating on the Internet movie database, therefore the model rely on the assumption that the movie is rated on this website. This also means that the model is biased toward movies that are present on IMDB. furthermore, in order to predict it better we need more data on attributes instead of critics and audience rating as they are colinnear. variables are implicitly have a relationship with the depdent variable, thus collinear.
